questions.query: How does your project contribute to the advancement of the Web3 grants ecosystem?
questions.explanation: Research on grant program design and effectiveness, Development of Web3 Grants tooling, Experiments with innovative funding mechanisms, Contributions to Web3 grants on-chain registry

questions.query: Describe your previous work or plans related to the Web3 grants ecosystem.
questions.explanation:
ICDevs.org has been issuing grants and running a bounty program for the last 3 years. Our focus has been on enabling ETH and EVM scalability via the the Internet Computer.  We are currently in the middle of a multi-month research and coding grant focused on developing a robust DAO and Grant framework baseline.  Current work can be viewed at https://daos.icdevs.org.

Our future goals are to conclude our current grant by producing a set of initial code blocks that can be used to help DAOs manage their grant process as well as for general DAO governance.  Once we have enabled these basic tools we will begin integrating them with the Internet Computer's ChainFusion technology that allows the IC to trustlessly communicate with EVM chains, thus bringing the functionality to those chains.

questions.query: How does your project create value for the Web3 grants ecosystem?
questions.explanation: Our deep research into the behavior of DAOs, funding mechanism, social coordination, and code expertise enables us to cast a wide net for opportunities in the grans space.

questions.query: Describe your team's expertise in your chosen focus area within Web3 grants. Include relevant experience, publications, or past projects.
questions.explanation: ICDevs.org has funded over $250k of grants. Through this experience we've seen a lot of what does and what does not work. Our research is pointing us toward a robust set of tools that interoperate with other protocols and provide scalability and gas-free, on-chain computation that opens new possibilities for grants programs.

questions.query: How do you plan to share insights, methodologies, or tools developed through your project with the Cartographer Syndicate and the broader Web3 grants community?
questions.explanation: Our research and tool development is all produced as opensource repositories on github. For example, our DAO research project is open for public consumption, feedback, and contribution at https://github.com/icdevsorg/icdevs_dao_lang

questions.query: How does your project contribute significantly to the Ethereum network's infrastructure? Please provide specific examples and metrics if available.
questions.explanation: As Vitalik says in places like https://vitalik.eth.limo/general/2023/03/31/zkmulticlient.html we need more clients! A motoko evm is the first step along the road for for us to have both a motoko based execution client and a consensus client. More about why this is important in the elevation section below. We are approaching having all opcodes available at https://github.com/icdevsorg/evm.mo and are seeking funding to build out the entire execution environment.

questions.query: Describe any pioneering development work in your project, particularly in enhancing privacy, interoperability, or user experience.
questions.explanation: The unique thing about a motoko execution and consensus client is that it can run in an trustless manner on the Internet Computer and (soon) AO ecosystem. This enables smart contracts and daos to operate their own nodes in the cloud controlled completely by smart contracts. Not private keys to be lost or founders to run away with the treasury. This tech relies on threshold ecdsa cryptography developed by DFINITY.

questions.query: What specific problems or challenges in the Ethereum ecosystem does your project address? How does your solution improve upon existing alternatives?
questions.explanation: Beyond adding another language to the diversity of execution clients, a motoko evm begins to create easy implementations of EVM event handlers, bots, and services that can be trustlessly held by DAOs and other applications without the need of complicated signing infrastructure.

questions.query: Outline your project's roadmap and how the grant funds will be used to achieve your development goals.
questions.explanation: We are about to run out of our funds procured during GG19 and GG20. New funds will be used to pay the project developer to flesh out the execution engine and storage mechanisms for the memory and state tries inside a motoko canister.  If enough are left over we can builds support libraries such as contract and memory importers that can allow soft forking of data from existing evm chains into the execution environment for transaction simulation and verification.

questions.query: How does your project contribute to the decentralization and security of the Ethereum network?
questions.explanation: The unique thing about a motoko execution and consensus client is that it can run in an trustless manner on the Internet Computer and (soon) AO ecosystem. This enables smart contracts and daos to operate their own nodes in the cloud controlled completely by smart contracts. Not private keys to be lost or founders to run away with the treasury. This tech relies on threshold ecdsa cryptography developed by DFINITY.

questions.query: How does your project contribute significantly to the Ethereum network's infrastructure? Please provide specific examples and metrics if available.
questions.explanation: We hope that by finishing our motoko evm we will be able to provide a way for people to rapidly deploy evms with "sufficient" decentralization for any number of L2 applications.  These may be for 'ethereal' evms that only exist for a short while or may be bots that take state and contracts from other evms, run simulations, and take action by submitting signed transactions to other chains.  With AIs on the rise, evms and the solidity language may become a trusted way for AIs to negotiate, transact, and settle real asset backed transactions. Motoko evms on will be able to provide this functionality.

questions.query: Describe any pioneering development work in your project, particularly in enhancing privacy, interoperability, or user experience.
questions.explanation: Motoko evms will be a great interoperability tool. By writing the op codes in motoko and building out the execution engine, DAOs will be able to control bots that can simulate transactions on other chains and take actions based off of the expected behavior.  Today, those contracts on other chains will need to have some kind of trusted setup with key shares.  The Internet Computer offers instant-on infrastructure decentralization with 13 and 34 node sub-nets that provide sufficient decentralization for many applications

questions.query: What specific problems or challenges in the Ethereum ecosystem does your project address? How does your solution improve upon existing alternatives?
questions.explanation: When launching a new network, reaching true decentralization beyond just multi-sig sharing can be difficult. Motoko evms on the Internet Computer could offer instant on evm networks with the push of a button. Control of these networks can be turned over to a DAO or blackholed under different strategies that make them tamperproof.

questions.query: Outline your project's roadmap and how the grant funds will be used to achieve your development goals.
questions.explanation:
Step 1. (Complete) Build all the op codes
Step 2. Build out the Execution Engine, Memories, and Trees
Step 3. Provide push button deployments of evms.
Step 4. Provide robust evm data loading  and simulation .
Step 5. Provide DAO controlled mainnet  and L2 clients.

questions.query: How does your project contribute to the decentralization and security of the Ethereum network?
questions.explanation: Adding an evm client in motoko is consistent with the multi-client ethos of Ethereum.
